For this task, I used Canva to create a one-page infographic on digital literacy. The goal was to make something that my batchmates could actually relate to and learn from, so I tried to keep it simple and visually clean. The infographic covers three topics — what digital literacy means, some useful tools for students, and basic safe internet practices.

The difficult part was finding the right images and icons. A lot of the good stuff on Canva requires a premium subscription, so I had to keep looking for free options that didn't look out of place in the design. That took more time than I expected honestly.

But the interesting part was the designing process itself. Every time I discovered a new feature or element in Canva, it gave me a new idea to work with. The more I built, the more creative I got — by the time I was finishing up the last section, it genuinely felt better than where I started.

Overall it was a pretty fun task and I didn't expect to enjoy using a design tool this much.
